{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:04:25.916982+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have all the information needed. Here's the complete walkthrough:\n\n---\n\n## Database Migrations in `rpnr-bench/T11_R01`\n\nThere are **3 migration files** in the `/migrations` directory, numbered sequentially. They are designed to be applied in numeric order:\n\n---\n\n### 1. `001_create_users.sql`\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    email        TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    display_name TEXT,\n    created_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Creates the `users` table — the foundational table of the application. It defines:\n\n- **`id`** — A `BIGSERIAL` auto-incrementing primary key (64-bit integer).\n- **`email`** — A `TEXT` column with a `UNIQUE` constraint and `NOT NULL`, ensuring every user has a distinct email address.\n- **`display_name`** — An optional `TEXT` field for the user's display name.\n- **`created_at`** — A `TIMESTAMPTZ` (timestamp with time zone) that defaults to the current time (`now()`) when a row is inserted.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `002_create_sessions.sql`\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Creates the `sessions` table for managing user authentication sessions. It defines:\n\n- **`id`** — A `UUID` primary key (randomly generated session identifier).\n- **`user_id`** — A `BIGINT` foreign key referencing `users(id)`. The `ON DELETE CASCADE` clause means if a user is deleted, all their sessions are automatically removed.\n- **`issued_at`** — Timestamp with time zone, defaulting to `now()` (when the session was created).\n- **`expires_at`** — Timestamp with time zone, marking when the session expires (must be explicitly provided on insert).\n\n---\n\n### 3. `003_add_session_index.sql`\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Adds a B-tree index on the `user_id` column of the `sessions` table. This is a performance optimization — it speeds up queries that look up sessions by user (e.g., \"find all active sessions for user X\" or \"invalidate all sessions for user X\"). This migration is separate from the table creation (002) because it's considered an additive performance change rather than part of the initial schema definition.\n\n---\n\n### Migration Order Summary\n\n| Order | File | Purpose |\n|-------|------|---------|\n| 1 | `001_create_users.sql` | Create the `users` table |\n| 2 | `002_create_sessions.sql` | Create the `sessions` table (depends on `users`) |\n| 3 | `003_add_session_index.sql` | Add performance index on `sessions.user_id` |\n\nThe numbering convention (`001`, `002`, `003`) establishes the application order, and the foreign key in migration `002` enforces that `001` must run first. Migration `003` is purely additive and can only be applied after `002` since the table must exist before an index can be built on it.\n\nThis is a straightforward, lightweight schema: users + sessions with a foreign key relationship and a lookup index — typical for a web application handling user authentication.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 840, "prompt_tokens": 5292, "total_tokens": 6132, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 66, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 4992}, "prompt_cache_hit_tokens": 4992, "prompt_cache_miss_tokens": 300}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "deepseek-v4-pro", "system_fingerprint": "fp_9954b31ca7_prod0820_fp8_kvcache_20260402", "id": "aa0c7e48-3613-4a30-a5c6-776f488b4aa3", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs